# Introduction

In this section, we'll introduce the essential networking protocols - TCP, UDP, and IP. Understanding these protocols is crucial for effective communication in computer networks.

# TCP - Transmission Control Protocol

## 2.1 Overview

TCP is a reliable, connection-oriented protocol. Learn about its fundamental characteristics and how it ensures data integrity during transmission.

## 2.2 Features

Explore the features that make TCP a reliable choice for applications that require accurate and ordered delivery of data.

## 2.3 Use Cases

Discover real-world scenarios where TCP is the preferred choice and understand its role in various applications.

# UDP - User Datagram Protocol

## 3.1 Overview

UDP is a lightweight, connectionless protocol. Learn about its simplicity and how it differs from TCP in terms of reliability.

## 3.2 Features

Explore the characteristics of UDP and understand when it is suitable for applications that prioritize speed over reliability.

## 3.3 Use Cases

Discover scenarios where UDP shines, such as in real-time applications and multimedia streaming.

# IP - Internet Protocol

## 4.1 Overview

IP is the foundation of the Internet. Gain insights into the role of IP in packet-switched networks and its significance in modern communication.

## 4.2 IP Addressing

Understand the concept of IP addressing, including IPv4 and IPv6, and how devices are identified on a network.

## 4.3 Routing

Explore how IP participates in routing, facilitating the delivery of data across interconnected networks.

# Conclusion

Summarize the key takeaways from the tutorial and emphasize the interconnected roles of TCP, UDP, and IP in facilitating seamless communication over networks.

